{{StructuredQuote|text=There's nowhere you can be that isn't where you're meant to be.|speaker=John Lennon}}<br>
{{Underline|4a4a4a}}

<center>
'''The Phantom''', also known as '''The Thing in the Dark''', has existed for about all of human history in the Backrooms and almost certainly longer. It lurks in absolute darkness without conventional spacial restraints, moving from one dark spot to the next and not needing to cross the space between. Suffice to say, any wanderer who finds themselves in the dark may become targeted by the '''Phantom'''. Even wanderers within range of good light sources are susceptible, though much less so. Any other factors besides darkness determining who the '''Phantom''' is more likely to come after are unknown, with the patterns seemingly being random.

When one is targeted, they will experience the entity stalking them in darkness that allows just the slightest impression of its form, moving back into the blackness and out again at different times and places. Scarce reports involving details of the entity's appearance entail many humanoid limbs, an unnaturally shaped head and an overall large figure. Only the victims are able to see the '''Phantom''', leading to theories that this may not even reflect its true form.

Should one stay in absolute darkness, the '''Phantom''' will torment them while remaining unseen. This may include things such has grabbing one's shoulder from behind, tripping one by seizing one's ankle, lacerating one's skin with what seem to be claws, and more. All this will quickly escalate into the victim meeting an agonizing death. There have been no sightings of the killing itself, but the aftermath is notorious for being brutal and gruesome. Occurrences such as bones left jutting out, deep gouges in the flesh and skin ripped off are just a few of many.

Even if one runs to and stays in the light indefinitely, the '''Phantom''' will continue shadowing them. When it is near, electrical lights are liable to flicker and even go out. Thus, relying on other light sources such as lanterns and candles are much more recommended in such predicaments. As long as there is enough nearby light, the entity cannot advance. It should be noted, however, that it can still reach out of total or near-thereof darkness or blow a gale so far that it extinguishes the flame. Additionally, those who find themselves in outdoor levels after being stalked will end up being confronted with an inescapable, light-obscuring fog. Therefore, many regard the '''Phantom''' as less of an entity and more of an unavoidable fate.<br><br>
{{Underline|4a4a4a}}


{{Imagebox|file=The-blank-vertical-white-grunge-old-classic-texture-paper-sheet-background-KGFMFA.png|opacity=1|align=left|outer-style=border: 0px; box-shadow: 0px 0px 10px #000000; margin: 1em 4em|inner-style=padding: 15px; font-family: Covered By Your Grace; font-size: 125%; color: #000000|text=
My name is Jason Daley. It's dark. I have only a candle with me, but I know it won't help. The Phantom has toyed with me long enough. Soon, it'll torture and kill me like so many others before myself.<br><br>
I'm not prepared to die. Who is? All I wanted was to settle somewhere livable in the Backrooms. Is that too much to ask? Settling somewhere in hell?

But no — I got desperate and thought myself lucky, and I wandered into the dark out of fear. Now I'll never escape it. My body probably won't even be found. The corridors around me feel endless now, stretching farther every time I try to walk. The candlelight barely reaches the walls anymore. Sometimes I think I can see shapes standing just beyond the glow, waiting for the flame to die.
<div class="blood" style="display: flex; justify-content: left; clear: both; position: relative">
<div style="z-index: 5">[[File:Blood-png-1.png|link=]]</div>

<div style="position: absolute; float: center; overflow: hidden; z-index: 4">
Why should I have to suffer? Couldn't it at least have been an entity that couldn't care less about causing pain?

This thing enjoys it. I know it does. Every distant footstep stops when I try to listen. Every strange sound fades away into silence. I know it wants me terrified before it finally comes close enough to touch.


I hear screams now. Echoing shrieks. Some sound well away, while the remainders sound like they're right in my ears, like they're erupting right beside me.

The candlelight is getting weaker and weaker. Its wax is running over my hand and burning my skin — I don't dare to drop it.

I think this is where I die. God sa v e  m  e.
}}
</center>


